    </table>

    <h2>Production Considerations</h2>

    <h3>Performance Optimization</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Caching:</strong> Cache frequent queries and embeddings</li>
      <li><strong>Async:</strong> Parallelize retrieval and embedding</li>
      <li><strong>Batch Processing:</strong> Bulk embed documents</li>
      <li><strong>Indexing:</strong> Pre-compute and optimize vector indices</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Cost Management</h3>
    <pre><code>Cost = Embedding Cost + Vector DB Cost + LLM Cost

Optimization:
- Use smaller/cheaper embedding models (384d vs 1536d)
- Quantize vectors (8-bit instead of 32-bit float)
- Limit retrieved chunks (top 3 vs top 10)
- Cache results for common queries
</code></pre>

    <h3>Monitoring</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Latency:</strong> P50, P95, P99 retrieval and generation times</li>
      <li><strong>Quality:</strong> User feedback, thumbs up/down</li>
      <li><strong>Retrieval:</strong> How often is context relevant?</li>
      <li><strong>Errors:</strong> Hallucinations, refusals, timeouts</li>
    </ul>

    <div class="callout warning">
      <div class="callout-title">⚠️ Common RAG Pitfalls</div>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Poor Chunking:</strong> Splits context mid-thought</li>
        <li><strong>Too Many Chunks:</strong> Exceeds LLM context window</li>
        <li><strong>Irrelevant Retrieval:</strong> Poor embedding model or query formulation</li>
        <li><strong>Stale Data:</strong> Forgetting to update index</li>
        <li><strong>No Fallback:</strong> LLM uses parametric knowledge when retrieval fails</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <h2>Key Terminology</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Grounding:</strong> Basing LLM output on retrieved facts</li>
      <li><strong>Hallucination:</strong> LLM generating false information</li>
      <li><strong>Dense Passage Retrieval (DPR):</strong> Embedding-based retrieval</li>
      <li><strong>Context Window:</strong> Maximum tokens LLM can process</li>
      <li><strong>Prompt Stuffing:</strong> Adding retrieved context to prompt</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Summary</h2>
    <div class="callout success">
      <div class="callout-title">✅ Key Takeaways</div>
      <ul>
        <li>RAG augments an LLM with retrieved context to improve grounding and freshness.</li>
        <li>Core components are ingestion/chunking, embeddings + indexing, retrieval, and generation.</li>
        <li>Chunking choices affect recall/precision and how much useful context fits into prompts.</li>
        <li>Hybrid retrieval (dense + sparse) and re-ranking can improve relevance for many queries.</li>
        <li>Good evaluation separates retrieval quality from generation faithfulness and usefulness.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <h3>What is RAG, in plain English?</h3>
    <p>RAG connects an LLM to a searchable knowledge base. When you submit a query, relevant documents are retrieved first and added to the prompt — so the model answers from your content, not just from its training data. This reduces hallucinations and keeps answers current without retraining the model.</p>

    <h3>When should I use RAG instead of fine-tuning?</h3>
    <p>Use RAG when your information changes frequently (policies, product docs, legal texts) or when you need to cite sources. Fine-tuning is better for changing how the model communicates — its tone, format, or specialized vocabulary — not for adding new factual knowledge. When in doubt, try RAG first: it is faster to set up and easier to update.</p>

    <h3>What is the main failure mode of a RAG system?</h3>
    <p>Two failure modes dominate. Retrieval gaps: the right document is not retrieved, so the model improvises and may hallucinate. Context overload: too many retrieved documents confuse or dilute the response. Both require separate evaluation — measure retrieval quality (did the right docs come back?) independently of generation quality (is the answer faithful to those docs?).</p>

    <h3>Do I need a vector database to build a RAG system?</h3>
    <p>Not always. For small corpora (under ~10,000 documents), in-memory tools like FAISS work well. A dedicated vector database (Pinecone, Weaviate, Qdrant, pgvector) becomes worthwhile when you need persistence, real-time updates, filtered search, or scale. Most managed RAG platforms include one by default.</p>

    <h3>How do I know if my RAG system is working well?</h3>
    <p>Evaluate retrieval and generation separately. For retrieval: measure whether the top results are relevant (precision) and whether important documents are not missed (recall). For generation: check faithfulness (does the answer stay within the retrieved context?) and answer relevance (does it address the question?). Tools like RAGAS automate much of this evaluation.</p>

    <h2>Reflection Questions for Technical Leaders</h2>
    <ol>
      <li>Your team proposes replacing a support chatbot with a RAG system over internal documentation. What would you need to know about document quality, access control, update frequency, and accuracy requirements before approving?</li>
      <li>A colleague suggests that RAG makes fine-tuning obsolete. What are the cases where this is true, and where is it not? How would you frame the trade-off for your engineering team?</li>
      <li>A production RAG system surfaces an incorrect answer in a customer-facing product. What steps would you take to diagnose whether the failure was a retrieval gap, a generation problem, or a data quality issue?</li>
      <li>You are evaluating two RAG platform vendors. Beyond accuracy and latency, what contractual, operational, and data-governance questions would you prioritize?</li>
    </ol>

